      mate - </b>An exciting game!  
    </p>
    <p>
    <b>   </b>  
    </p>
    <p>
    The following position from another recent club game (see diagram) offers the opportunity to explore several important common tactical motifs, namely the <span class=
      "cleanuphtml-2">pin</span> and the <span class="cleanuphtml-2">back-rank mate</span>. White is a R and 4 pawns down but with his next move <b>1.Nc4,</b> which forks and double attacks my "e"
    and "a" pawns, threatens to regain material. In response I moved <b>1..., Qc7</b>, which reinforced my "a" pawn and set a potential trap if the "d" pawn were to be captured. White then did
    fall into the trap and make the capture by <b>2.Nxd6</b> (2.Rxd6 would lose the Nc4 to my Q) . My response was to <span class="cleanuphtml-2">pin</span> the N by <b>2.., Rfd8, </b>doubling on
    it and threatening to win it.  Now moving the N would of course forfeit his R. And if White were to counterattack my Q by moving 3.Nb5 or 3.Ne8, I would sacrifice the Q to force mate on d1
    (the vulnerable back-rank!) with the R after 3...., Rxd2; 4.Nxc7, Rd1 mate.  White instead played <b>3.Qxe5</b>, thinking to reinforce the N and gain a pawn in the process but overlooking
    that this left the Nc1 hanging
    </p>
    <p>
    to 3<b>..., Qxc1+</b>.  He then had no choice but to either resign or throw himself on the spear by <b>4.Rd1, Qxd1+; 5.Qe1, Qxe1 mate</b> - the fatal curse of the vulnerable back rank!
    </p>
    <p>
    <b> Anon.</b>
    </p>
